OWASP Top 10 API Security Risks (OWASP API Top 10)
🔷 Introduction

APIs (Application Programming Interfaces) are widely used in modern web and mobile applications. However, they are highly exposed and can be vulnerable to attacks.
The OWASP has published the OWASP API Top 10, which lists the most critical security risks specific to APIs.

These risks help developers secure APIs and protect sensitive data.

🔥 OWASP API Top 10 Threats
1. Broken Object Level Authorization (BOLA)
Occurs when APIs do not properly verify user access to objects
Attackers can access data of other users

Example: Accessing another user’s profile by changing ID

2. Broken Authentication
Weak authentication mechanisms
Leads to account takeover

Example: Weak passwords or missing token validation

3. Broken Object Property Level Authorization
Improper access control at property level
Users can modify sensitive fields

Example: Changing user role from “user” to “admin”

4. Unrestricted Resource Consumption
No limits on API usage
Can lead to DoS (Denial of Service)

Example: Unlimited requests crashing server

5. Broken Function Level Authorization
Missing checks for user roles
Unauthorized access to functions

Example: Normal user accessing admin API

6. Unrestricted Access to Sensitive Business Flows
No restriction on critical processes
Abuse of business logic

Example: Placing multiple fake orders

7. Server Side Request Forgery (SSRF)
API fetches remote data without validation
Attackers access internal systems

Example: Requesting internal server URLs

8. Security Misconfiguration
Improper API configuration
Default settings, open endpoints

Example: Debug mode enabled in production

9. Improper Inventory Management
Untracked or outdated APIs
Exposed old versions

Example: Old API version still accessible

10. Unsafe Consumption of APIs
Trusting external APIs without validation
Leads to data compromise

Example: Using third-party API without verifying response
